Through Urban Gardening -- tPart IV: Critical Connections -- tIntroduction -- t16 Interlocking Crises, Intersectional Visions: Ecofeminist Political Economy in Conversation with Degrowth -- t17 Dependency, Delinking and Degrowth in a New Developmental Era: Debates from Argentina -- t18 Degrowth and Psychoanalysis: From Transition to Transformation -- t19 Degrowth Disagreements with Marxism: Critical Perspectives on the Fetishisation of Value and Productivity -- t20 Not Just Newer, but Fewer: A Bridge Between Ecomodernism and Degrowth? -- tPart V: Degrowth and the Global South -- tIntroduction -- t21 From Marxist Development Theories to Their Translation in the Degrowth Discourse: Transforming Unequal International Structures for Environmental Sustainability -- t22 Radical Ecological Democracy: Reflections from the South on Degrowth -- t23 Degrowth Beyond the Metropole: Theory and Praxis for a Revolutionary Degrowth -- t24 Growing Degrowth: Alliances with Environmental Movements in the Global South -- t25 ‘For the Greater Good’– Green Sacrifice Zones and Subaltern Resistance: The Politics and Potential of Degrowth and Post-Extractivist Futures -- tList of Figures -- tAbout the Editors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDegrowth has emerged as one of the most exciting, and contested, fields of research into the drivers of global heating, ecological collapse, and economic injustice. The perspective is both a critique of existing growth-based models of development, which it argues have put humanity on a collision course with non-negotiable ecological limits, and a vision for a brighter future in which humans and non-humans alike can flourish. By putting an end to growth-seeking economic development and boundless energetic and material throughputs, degrowth’s proponents suggest we can build an economy that meets the material needs of people and planet for generations to come. This handbook’s contributions signal the importance of degrowth across multiple disciplines and practices. Along the way, they grapple with some of the most critical questions, ideological assumptions, policies, and social struggles of our time. The handbook approaches degrowth as a loosely knit and developing set of interdisciplinary propositions about what it might take to achieve a world of human and non-human flourishing. Contributors explore, challenge, and critique degrowth’s propositions and its prospects of shaping scholarly agendas, policy frameworks, and social movements. Essays consider degrowth from a variety of empirical and theoretical vantages, including urban design, architecture, political economy, political ecology, critical geography, and political theory. This integrative approach, at once critical and constructive, aims to preserve for readers the sense of possibility that has drawn people to degrowth scholarship thus far.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNegative growth (Economics). 4aNachhaltigkeit. 4aPostwachstum. 4asoziale Gerechtigkeit. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh  aDegrowth.  aconsumption.  aenvironment.  apolitical ecology.  asustainability.1 aAlenda-Demoutiez, Juliette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexander, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarlow, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaumann, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroadfield, Chloe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrokow-Loga, Anton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurdon, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu